</p><p>The additional terms &#x003b1;<italic><sub>X</sub></italic><sub>2</sub><italic>x</italic><sub>2<italic>i</italic></sub> and &#x003b1;<italic><sub>X</sub></italic><sub>3</sub><italic>x</italic><sub>3<italic>i</italic></sub> represent causal effects of <italic>X</italic><sub>2</sub> and <italic>X</italic><sub>3</sub> (which were evaluated first) on <italic>X</italic><sub>1</sub>. We set &#x003b1;<italic><sub>U</sub></italic><sub>1</sub>, &#x003b1;<italic><sub>U</sub></italic><sub>2</sub>, and &#x003b1;<italic><sub>U</sub></italic><sub>3</sub> equal to 0.3 (the first scenario considered above) and took 9 values of the parameters &#x003b1;<italic><sub>X</sub></italic><sub>2</sub> and &#x003b1;<italic><sub>X</sub></italic><sub>3</sub> (Table&#x000a0;<xref ref-type="table" rid="KWU283TB2">2</xref>). All other parameters were taken as in the original simulation study.
